{"paperId": "4fcd94cd8ee484004588c60531952bc56c3af67b", "abstract": "Linear recurrent models, such as State Space Models (SSMs) and Linear Recurrent Units (LRUs), have recently shown state-of-the-art performance on long sequence modelling benchmarks. Despite their success, they come with a number of drawbacks, most notably their complex initialisation and normalisation schemes. In this work, we address some of these issues by proposing RotRNN -- a linear recurrent model which utilises the convenient properties of rotation matrices. We show that RotRNN provides a simple model with fewer theoretical assumptions than prior works, with a practical implementation that remains faithful to its theoretical derivation, achieving comparable scores to the LRU and SSMs on several long sequence modelling datasets.", "venue": "", "year": 2024, "citationCount": 0, "influentialCitationCount": 0, "openAccessPdf": null, "tldr": {"model": "tldr@v2.0.0", "text": "It is shown that RotRNN provides a simple model with fewer theoretical assumptions than prior works, with a practical implementation that remains faithful to its theoretical derivation, achieving comparable scores to the LRU and SSMs on several long sequence modelling datasets."}, "embedding": {"model": "specter_v2", "vector": [0.23830346763134003, 0.5710911154747009, -0.4812203049659729, -0.04370174556970596, 0.40732699632644653, -0.28600946068763733, 0.834058403968811, -0.3549882471561432, -0.3940419852733612, -0.45796069502830505, 0.9914217591285706, 0.016073282808065414, 0.5191900134086609, 0.38749924302101135, -0.16698001325130463, -0.046721771359443665, -0.9918442964553833, -0.03551749140024185, 0.057285062968730927, -0.09892015159130096, 0.17426683008670807, -0.21177375316619873, -0.795448362827301, -0.2736523449420929, -0.4480111300945282, 0.40357503294944763, 0.23914720118045807, 0.9616002440452576, -0.34090858697891235, 0.835738480091095, 0.4936782717704773, -0.15471911430358887, 0.5233905911445618, -0.66798222064971